			<title>Max Volume Limiter Software</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78183-Max-Volume-Limiter-Software&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 09 Oct 2015 03:30:38 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>Idiotically not every consumer OS includes built-in software that can limit or normalize volume of its audio. I listen to amateur erotic audio a lot and they will make your ears bleed when they are rather enthralled so I have tried out a few different tools that limit or normalize volume, which is...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Idiotically not every consumer OS includes built-in software that can limit or normalize volume of its audio. I listen to amateur erotic audio a lot and they will make your ears bleed when they are rather enthralled so I have tried out a few different tools that limit or normalize volume, which is especially helpful when wearing headphones. <br />
<br />
Here is one that is cross platform and free that works pretty well: <a href="http://loudmax.blogspot.ru" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://loudmax.blogspot.ru</a><br />
<br />
Not sure why Apple has not included such software as they make audio software so this is a pretty trivial solution in comparison.<br />
<br />
There is also Boom 2 on the App Store, but it is OS X only. Out of the paid solutions I think it is the easiest to use. Its GUI is pretty decent. <br />
<br />
VLC includes the ability to normalize audio and works the best I think but it can't hook into a web browser's audio.</div>

